Coming of Age Under Trump: Online Appendix

Author

Nikolaos Vichos

Introduction

This document is the online appendix for the paper âComing of Age Under Trump The Effect of First Electoral Exposure in a Trump Election on Long-Term Support for Press Freedomâ Here I have included additional, mainly methodological, details not included in the main body of the paper.

Regression Design

Since linear models estimated via ordinary least squares may miss subtle non-linearities in how the outcome evolves with age, I estimate a more flexible version of the RDD.1 This can be expressed as:

\[ Y_i = \alpha + \tau D_i + f(X_i - c) + \varepsilon_i \]

Where:

  • \(Y_i\) is the outcome, measuring attitudes toward media freedom
  • \(D_i\) is an indicator equal to 1 if individual \(i\)âs age exceeds the cutoff (i.e., they were just eligible to vote in 2012), and 0 otherwise.2
  • \(\tau\) is the parameter of interest, capturing the size of the discontinuity at the thresholdâthat is, the causal effect of being first eligible to vote in 2012 rather than in 2016.
  • \(X_i\) is the running variable, the respondentâs age in years in 2020.
  • \(f(X_i - c)\) denotes a flexible function (e.g., first- or second-order polynomial) of the centered running variableâdistance from the cutoff \(c\).
  • \(c = 26\) is the cutoff point, so \(X_i - c\) represents the running variable centered at the threshold.
  • \(\varepsilon_i\) is an error term.

In my analysis, I estimated a series of sharp RD models using local polynomial regression. Each model used local linear estimation (polynomial order = 1) and MSE-optimal bandwidth selection to obtain the treatment effect at the cutoff.

Index Construction

This section documents the construction of the indices, including item wording, internal consistency, factor structure, and rescaling.

Item Wordings

The tables below provided the exact question wording for each item included in the indices. Most responses were in a 5- or 7-point Likert scale.

Media Freedom Attitudes Items and Survey Wording
Shortened Name Survey Question
Free Press First, how important is it that news organizations are free to criticize political leaders?
Concern for Media Undermining How concerned are you that some people in the government today might want to undermine the news mediaâs ability to serve as a check on governmental power?
Journalist Access Do you favor, oppose, or neither favor nor oppose elected officials restricting journalistsâ access to information about government decision-making?

Internal Consistency

To evaluate the internal consistency of the items used in the indices, I computed Cronbachâs Î± for each the aforementioned set of items. Both the raw and the standardized alpha (Î± = 0.7) show acceptable consistency (Taber 2018).

Factor Structure

Next, I used principal axis factoring (no rotation) to assess whether the three items capture a single underlying construct. Based on the Kaiser criterion (eigenvalue > 1) a single factor was retained for each item. Factor loadings for each indexâs selected items were above 0.35, confirming unidimensionality.

Index Rescaling

Each index is constructed by extracting individual scores on the first factor and rescaling them to range from 0 to 1 using minâmax normalization. Even though higher values indicate lower endorsement for radical right attitudes during the process of index construction, this is for visualization and interpretability purposes, due to the specific design of the rdrobust package (calonico2025?). In the package, the threshold is âcrossedâ from left to rightâhence, normally, a positive effect would suggest an increase in nativist, authoritarian, or populist attitudes among those who voted for the first time in 2012. However, for clearer comprehension, the results have been reversed, and the indices can be interpreted as indicating decreasing support for each of the three ideological features. However, strictly speaking, the indices indicate the opposite direction in their construction. For details on the process of index construction, refer to the replication code file.

Robustness Checks

I present the robustness checks conducted the two models (Simple vs Controls) and for the three different RD estimates (Conventional, Bias-Adjusted, Bias-Adjusted with Robust SEs). I first present them for the full sample and then for the different subgroup. Due to their large number, however, they are quite difficult to navigate.

To narrow them down a bit I only focus on outcomes where there was at least one significant result (i.e., not populism) and across groups that also had at least one significant result (i.e., not partisans or democrats)
